y're interested in reaching their destinations ... everyone rides as upright as if they were sitting at the kitchen table back at home.' Photograph: Denis Doyle/AP","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-389141379","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2011/4/15/1302874879635/Dutch-cyclist-003.jpg","typeData":{"source":"AP","photographer":"Denis Doyle","altText":"Dutch cyclist","height":"84","credit":"Denis Doyle/AP","caption":"How the Dutch do it ... 'People cycle because they're interested in reaching their destinations ... everyone rides as upright as if they were sitting at the kitchen table back at home.' Photograph: Denis Doyle/AP","width":"140"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"The Bicycle Book by Bella Bathurst – review","webPublicationDate":"2011-04-10T03:00:00Z","sectionName":"Books","sectionId":"books","id":"lifeandstyle/2011/apr/10/bicycle-book-bella-bathurst-review","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2011/4/6/1302084751072/Music-festival-with-envir-003.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/2z8v6","standfirst":"Keen cyclist Bella Bathurst mixes obsession with wit in her entertaining study of humanity on two wheels","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-03T17:21:27Z","body":"<p>The bicycle is the most popular form of transport on the planet. It has been for more than a century. In that time, we've devised numerous reasons and ways to ride this eminently simple machine. From professional track cyclists to BMX free riders, via mountain bikers, cycle couriers, paratroopers and porteurs, Bella Bathurst focuses her sharp eye on most cycle tribes in this timely book.</p><p>Save for a chapter on the author building her own bicycle frame, Bathurst lets people who actually live on their bicycles do much of the talking. Charlie Wegelius, the seasoned English racing cyclist, dissects the professional peloton with cool clarity; Danny MacAskill, the youthful YouTube sensation, discusses riding urban street furniture; the Atherton siblings talk glamour, risk and corporate sponsorship in downhill mountain biking; and the great Scottish cyclist Graeme Obree, who broke the World Hour Record twice, reflects upon riding as an obsession.</p><p>In fact, obsession is a leitmotif of the book: researching it, Bathurst notes, \"I kept bumping up against the same thing, that bicycles are just a form of self-medication for the obsessed.\" The other constant in this episodic analysis of the bicycle and its aficionados is the elegant prose: like a tail wind pressing on your back, it propels the reader through the pages.</p><p>There are errors – Tom Simpson died in 1967, not 1957 – and some of the digressions – hand-pulled rickshaws in Calcutta and London taxi drivers, to name two – tell us little. Bathurst excels when she has something to get her cogs into. There is an evocative account of off-road, adventure cycling in Britain in the early 20th century, and a wonderful introduction to cycle sport: \"If half of racing is about masochism, then the other half is about sadism.\" The cultural influence of the cycle-messenger scene – \"full of nomads with a few long-stay patients\" – is adroitly examined. The evaluation of the role of the bicycle in the emancipation of women is a must-read. And her observations of the phenomenon now known as the \"mamil\" (\"middle-aged men in Lycra\") are witty: at a trade show full of two-wheel bling, Bathurst likens men \"waiting in line to give each bike an experimental lift by its crossbar\" to \"dogs and lampposts\".</p><p>Inevitably, a book considering the bicycle in all its past and present forms touches on cycle advocacy. As Bathurst notes, in recent decades the bicycle has been the \"transport system's perpetual underdog\". A chapter on the Netherlands explains how the Dutch cycle \"because they're interested in reaching their destinations\". Bathurst flags up the failure of UK transport policy at government level. More tellingly, she points out that organisations supposed to promote cycling have sometimes done the opposite. The Cyclists' Touring Club, founded in 1878, opposed the establishment of a national network of cycle paths in the 1930s, fearing it might affect cyclists' rights to use the road. You could argue we're still struggling with the consequences of this now.</p><p>Our ancestors thought the bicycle one of their greatest achievements. This idea is coming back into vogue in western society. Bicycles are fashionable – that may not last, but it's indicative of how urban infrastructure design, transport policy, environmental and health concerns, the price of oil, city bike hire schemes, the profile of cycle sport and leisure practices are all driving the bicycle back to the centre of public consciousness. With <em>The Bicycle Book</em>, Bathurst adds her voice to the call that we are now at the dawn of a new golden age of this versatile machine.</p>","headline":"The Bicycle Book by Bella Bathurst – review","trailText":"<p>Keen cyclist Bella Bathurst mixes obsession with wit in her entertaining study of humanity on two wheels, says <strong>Robert Penn</strong></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"38","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Observer","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2011/4/6/1302084751072/Music-festival-with-envir-003.jpg","wordcount":"586","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"373303638","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"4545999","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Robert Penn","newspaperEditionDate":"2011-04-10T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1541112","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2011-04-30T22:59:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/apr/10/bicycle-book-bella-bathurst-review","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.gua