ng-popularity-falls","fields":{"secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2009/6/15/1245066934303/Old-bicycles-on-the-landi-004.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/28g3m","standfirst":"Survey shows that for three-quarters of Britons, learning to ride a bike is no longer a childhood rite of passage","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-05-19T11:30:54Z","body":"<p></p><p>British youngsters would rather stay at home and play computer games or watch TV than learn how to ride a bike, according to research released today.</p><p></p><p>A report carried out by Kellogg's reveals that one in three homes in the UK are now bike-free zones, while nearly three-quarters of Britons (74%) admit that the attractions of a TV or computer screen have replaced learning to ride a bicycle as a childhood rite of passage.</p><p></p><p>The research also shows that the latest games consoles such as the Xbox and PS3 have replaced the BMX as the childhood accessory of choice, with parents admitting they had spent double on computer games and consoles during the past decade than they had on bikes or cycling equipment.</p><p></p><p>This week is <a href=\"http://www.bikeweek.org.uk/\" title=\"National bike week\">national bike week</a> – a celebration of cycling designed to encourage people to get on their bikes and explore their local communities. This year it will urge families to take up cycling as a regular activity.</p><p>According to the research, almost half of UK parents also admitted they never ride a bike anymore, while nearly half confessed that learning to ride a bike was not as important for children nowadays as it was during their own childhood. One in five parents in London said they were not going to bother teaching their children at all.</p><p></p><p></p><p>More than half of those questioned blamed a lack of local cycle routes for their reluctance to cycle, with 52% describing their home town or city as unsuitable for cycling. They also cited road safety concerns and lack of time as the major obstacles to cycling.</p><p></p><p>Liverpool is the city with the fewest cyclists, with 48% of households admitting to not owning any bikes.</p><p></p><p>Respondents also said that they would be more likely to cycle if VAT on bicycles was removed, while one in five claimed that improved government schemes or incentives would encourage them to get back on their bikes.</p>","headline":"Bicycle appeal punctured by computers and TV","trailText":"Survey shows that for three-quarters of Britons, learning to ride a bike is no longer a childhood rite of passage","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2009/6/15/1245066934303/Old-bicycles-on-the-landi-004.jpg","wordcount":"315","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"348886584","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"2121797","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Rebecca Smithers, Consumer affairs correspondent","internalPageCode":"1232113","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2009-06-18T12:09:36Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2009/jun/15/cycling-popularity-falls","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/money/2009/jun/15/cycling-popularity-falls","tags":[{"id":"money/consumer-affairs","webTitle":"Consumer affairs","type":"keyword","sectionId":"money","sectionName":"Money","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/consumer-affairs","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/money/consumer-affairs","references":[]},{"id":"money/money","webTitle":"Money","type":"keyword","sectionId":"money","sectionName":"Money","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/money","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/money/money","references":[]},{"id":"profile/rebeccasmithers","webTitle":"Rebecca Smithers","rcsId":"GNL002880","r2ContributorId":"16313","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-imag