search the best bike for your needs. The site has stacks of information on different types of cycles, from touring bikes to tandems, including information on what kinds of trip they suit, the pros and cons and how much you should expect to pay.</p><h2>Do some research</h2><p>A quick search on the internet shows how much prices differ between outlets – the price of one model ranged from £680 to £829, so it's important to shop around. The price quoted could be without necessary accessories and lower specifications (gears, brakes and so on). You may end up buying what you think is a bargain only to find yourself paying £100 for additional items or upgrades, so make sure you compare like-for-like.</p><p>Visit <a href=\"http://www.myvouchercodes.co.uk\" title=\"\">myvouchercodes.co.uk</a> for the latest money-off promotions and discounts. At the time of writing, Amazon and Halfords are among those offering promotions on bikes and accessories. Factor all this in when you are comparing prices.</p><h2>Go shopping</h2><p>When you know what you want and have an idea of where it is available for the best price, hit the high street. Don't assume you have to pay full price as you may be able to get some money off, or persuade the retailer to throw in some extras like accessories or a free first service.</p><p>A wet weekday in May would be a good time to approach the shops; a traditionally quiet retail day with poor weather – shoppers will be buying brollies rather than bikes!</p><p>Let's assume the price range of the bike you're after is between £399 and £475. Call an outlet offering a good price, but not the best – in this case, one that is selling the bike for £420. Base your conversation along the following lines:</p><p><strong>You: </strong>\"Does the Speedex M6L come with mudguards already fitted?\" (You know it does in some stores, but not this one.)</p><p><strong>Shopkeeper: </strong>\"No, but we can fit them for £14.99\"</p><p><strong>You: </strong>\"I can already buy the bike elsewhere for £399; many stores include mudguards in the price. I would like to buy locally, however £420 is too expensive compared to other places, if you could do £360 including mudguards, I would buy now.\"</p><p><strong></strong><strong>Shopkeeper: </strong>\"No, £360 is too cheap.\" (Notice the shopkeeper didn't say no to a discount, just to your offer.)</p><p><strong>You: </strong>\"OK, what could you offer?\"</p><p><strong>Shopkeeper: </strong>\"We could offer £390 with mudguards.\"</p><p><strong>You: </strong>\"I'll have to think about that. However, if it means lowering the price by a further £10 for me to buy off you rather than someone else, would you be prepared to do that?\"</p><p><strong>Shopkeeper: </strong>\"Yes, OK.\"</p><p><strong>The final flurry</strong> With a similar conversation to the one above, speak to your number one store, adding in your new offer. As a final deal-breaker, perhaps ask them something similar to: \"If you include a helmet for £375, I shall buy it from you NOW.\"</p><h2>Get an even better deal</h2><p>Your employer may be signed up for the government's <a href=\"http://www.dft.gov.uk/pgr/sustainable/cycling/cycletoworkschemeimplementat5732\" title=\"Government Cycle to Work scheme\">Cycle to Work scheme</a>. This is a salary sacrifice scheme whereby your employer buys the bike and loans it to you at a monthly cost deducted from your salary.</p><p>The payments are taken from your gross salary so you avoid income tax and national insurance payments on the amount, as well as savings your employer may make from VAT. You may then be eligible for buying the bike at a fair price from your employee (individual company rules apply) at the end of the loan period. This system does not work for all, but is worth looking into.</p><p>If your employer is not yet signed up, try out your new-found skills of persuasion on them!</p><h2>Second-hand bargains</h2><p>If you want to bag a bargain and are happy with a second-hand bike, the one mentioned earlier priced at £829 was sold \"almost new\" on <a href=\"http://www.ebay.co.uk\" title=\"\">eBay</a> for £360 recently. Also, someone in your local area may be giving away their cycle on <a href=\"http://www.freecycle.org\" title=\"\">Freecycle</a> – you'll be helping the environment at the same time. Either way, make sure you check the brakes and roadworthiness of the bike before you buy.</p>","headline":"Freewheeling your way to a bargain bicycle","trailText":"<p><strong>Marc Lockley </strong>is<strong> the Negotiator </strong>. This week he looks at the best way to save money when buying a bicycle</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2008/08/21/bikes140x84.jpg","wordcount":"752","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"347422804","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"2005353","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Marc Lockley","internalPageCode":"1216373","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2009-05-23T23:05:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2009/may/19/buying-bicycle-saving-money","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/money/2009/may/19/buying-bicycle-saving-money","tags":[{"id":"money/saving-money","webTitle":"Saving money","type":"keyword","sectionId":"money","sectionName":"Money","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/saving-money","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/money/saving-money","references":[]},{"id":"money/series/the-negotiator","webTitle":"The Negotiator","description":"You can save money on almost everything if you know how, says Marc Lockley, author of How to pay less for more. Each fortnight he offers tips on driving a bargain – from beating down the cost of a mobile phone contract to paying less for your gym membership. You could save thousands","type":"series","sectionId":"money","sectionName":"Money","webUrl":"http://www.theguar